texts.text: *groan*
>Yoshitsune, Hinokagutsuchi, and Hachiman slay the demons.
>Exhausted, the demons disappear.
...Have they fallen?
>The Aura Gate falls silent.
>The light air carries the faint scent of earth and wind.
...Yoshitsune.
Don't speak, Lord Hachiman.
Like Yoritomo, who made a world for the samurai and our clan,
I wanted to achieve something.
But my eyes were clouded. I deserve your rebuke,
even though I've only ever wanted to help those I love.
I'm ashamed.
Just let me just quietly fade away...
You for real, Yoshitsune? You gonna disappear for good?
But you did nothin' wrong.
He's right! Don't sweat it.
Generals are responsible for their subordinates.
I don't know what form I'll take next, but...
I hope I can help someone.
Yoshitsune...
Wait, Yoshitsune.
Before you decide, hear my proposal.
Proposal?
Your heart yearns to live for others.
Therefore, you should help the Liberators protect this land.
You think so?
Help? Why should I, Lord Hachiman?
For your own sake.
As guardian deity of this nation and the Minamoto clan,
I have my own solemn destiny.
This time, I feared you had become a fallen hero.
Although now I'm certain your resolve is pure,
it is tragic your past wounds would lead you to oblivion.
Lord Hachiman...
Yoshitsune. Why not stay in this world a while longer?
Mingling with mortals living for the moment is sure to heal you.
Liberators, what say you?
Our door is always open, buddy.
And he's a total powerhouse.
Your assistance will surely bolster our morale.
The verdict is in.
So, Yoshitsune. What say you?
Well, you all seem to be skilled masters of your trade.
I'll leave it to you.
I might lend a hand on occasion if you earn my respect.
Oh my, someone's shy. Well, I suppose we have a deal.
But don't get used to it!
I won't be much help if I don't train daily!
Well said. Then you've made your decision.
Yoshitsune, you have the pure, childlike heart of a hero.
I shall continue to watch over you.
Right! Thanks, Lord Hachiman.
Later, Liberators! Stay diligent!
>Yoshitsune disappears without looking back.
>The ownerless Aura Gate soon crumbles.
Well, a god like myself must return to his duties.
Thanks. We owe ya one, Hinokagutsuchi.
You too, Hachiman.
Certainly.
May we meet again, Liberators.
Be careful around fire.
>Several days later...
>The Liberators visit a shrine dedicated to Hachiman.
Why's it so crowded? Not like anything special is going on.
Is Hachiman that big a draw?
You bet.
I mean, it's why he's so strong. Faith moves mountains.
Have you brought news today, Liberators?
Yep.
There's been a steady drop in fires since the incident.
Probably 'cause Hinokagutsuchi went home.
Excellent.
Even so, it's difficult to eliminate them entirely.
Fire is a fearsome thing.
It bestows many blessings,
yet it can also reduce all that is precious to cinders.
Upon his birth, Hinokagutsuchi burned his own mother to death.
Those with power...
They must understand the extent of their own strength.
Yes, I agree.
Purity is no different.
Yoshitsune's naivete,
for better or worse, is what provoked this past incident.
That's the power of purity, huh?
Indeed.
Such innocence, passion, and natural talent...
They can lift him to great heights.
Yoshitsune will attract many followers once more.
I believe you Liberators possess the same strength.
However, one misstep can have dire consequences.
Reliance on demonic power will only end in self-loathing.
Gotcha.
We'll take your god-given words to heart and stay humble.
Still, let's be real here.
You said you're impartial or whatever,
but you were worried sick about Yoshitsune, right?
Hmm?
I had the same thought.
You showed it only at the very end.
C'mon, admit it. You didn't want him to end up a "fallen hero,"
and that's why you called us, right?
...You all have quite the memory.
I did some research afterward,
and apparently Hachiman is the divine spirit of an ancient emperor.
If you used to be human, you'd totally understand human nature!
*stare*
Open up more.
A rather meaningful stare, that.
So, I should emulate Yoshitsune?
...Hmph. That is fair, perhaps.
I am a god. I worry for all of humanity in equal measure.
Ugh, that old story!
*chuckle* Our human brains can't fathom how a god really feels.
So, let's just invent our own interpretations.
Do let's. That too is human nature,
something we can do thanks to our human hearts.
